*After creating a new repository, I am presented with the following verbiage:*

If you already have code ready to be pushed to this repository then run this in your terminal.

{{cd existing-project}}
 {{git init}}
 {{git add --all}}
 {{git commit -m "Initial Commit"}}
 {{git remote add origin ssh://git@my-server.domain.com/project/my-new-repo.git}}
 {{git push -u origin master}}

 

*However, after following this advice I am presented with an error.*

 

{{C:\my\project>git push -u origin master}}
 {{To ssh://my-server.domain.com/project/my-new-repo.git}}
 {{! [rejected] master -> master (fetch first)}}
 {{error: failed to push some refs to 'ssh://my-server.domain.com/project/my-new-repo.git'}}
 {{hint: Updates were rejected because the remote contains work that you do}}
 {{hint: not have locally. This is usually caused by another repository pushing}}
 {{hint: to the same ref. You may want to first integrate the remote changes}}
 {{hint: (e.g., 'git pull ...') before pushing again.}}
 {{hint: See the 'Note about fast-forwards' in 'git push --help' for details.}}

 

*After following the hint, I run into yet another roadblock:*

{{C:\my\project>git pull origin master}}
 {{From ssh://my-server.domain.com/project/my-new-repo.git}}
 {{* branch master -> FETCH_HEAD}}
 {{fatal: refusing to merge unrelated histories}}

 

 *This is a poor user experience, which can be solved with a simple update to the verbiage on the page. This is my suggestion:*

 If you already have code ready to be pushed to this repository then run this in your terminal.

{{cd existing-project}}
 {{git init}}
 {{git add --all}}
 {{git commit -m "Initial Commit"}}
 {{git remote add origin ssh://git@my-server.domain.com/project/my-new-repo.git}}
 {{git pull origin master --allow-unrelated-histories}}
 {{git push -u origin master}}

*Take note of the additional pull command between "remote add" and "push". This simple change will drastically improve user experience.*

*Thank you*

h2. Summery
Bitbucket sends a web hook to a Bitbucket Mirror when a repository is updated.  If this hook fails to comunicate to the Bitbucket Mirror OR fails before establishing a connection, a generic {{failed with an error}} message will be logged.

h2. Actual Results
{noformat}
111-11-11 11:11:11,111 INFO  [ForkJoinPool.commonPool-worker-*]  c.a.w.i.p.DefaultWebhookDispatcher Webhook invocation [...] 
	failed with an error
{noformat}

h2. Expected Results
{noformat}
111-11-11 11:11:11,111 INFO  [ForkJoinPool.commonPool-worker-*]  c.a.w.i.p.DefaultWebhookDispatcher Webhook invocation [...] 
	failed with an error <More data here>
{noformat} 
Any data that can be provided about why the error occurred; 404, Internal server error, ect.

Hi, 

I currently installed Bitbucket Server and having troubles accessing the marketplace. Bitbucket Server 5.7.0.

If I use a filter (featured, highest-rated, popular etc.) on "All Categories" (use of German "Alle Kategorien"), a warning appears in logfile:
{quote}"GET /rest/plugins/1.0/available/featured HTTP/1.0" c.a.upm.pac.AddonMarketplaceQueries Marketplace product query failed: com.atlassian.marketplace.client.MpacException$ServerError: 400: category: Allowable values are "Admin tools", "Blueprints", "Build management", "Charts & diagramming", "Continuous integration", "Custom fields", "Dashboard gadgets", "Design tools", "Document management", "Documentation", "Email", "IT & helpdesk", "Integrations", "Language packs", "Macros", "Messaging", "Mobile", "Monitoring", "Project management", "Reports", "Repository connectors", "Repository hooks", "Shared workflows", "Source code", "Tasks", "Testing & QA", "Themes & styles", "Time tracking", "Utilities", "Workflow"
{quote}
After taking a look into the source code I found the bug: An i18n error. I have currently a Starter Licence, so I can not report the bug to Atlassian directly :(

 

